[[Uzbekistan]] had a total primary energy supply ([[TPES]]) of 48.28 [[tonne of oil equivalent|Mtoe]] in 2012.<ref name=iea2012 /> Electricity consumption was 47.80 [[TWh]]. 
The majority of primary energy came from fossil fuels, with natural gas, coal and oil the main sources. Hydroelectricity, the only significant renewable source in the country, accounted for about 2% of the primary energy supply. 
Natural gas is the source for 73.8% of electricity production, followed by hydroelectricity with 21.4%.<ref name=iea2012>{{cite web|title=Uzbekistan|url=http://www.iea.org/statistics/statisticssearch/report/?year=2012&country=Uzbekistan&product=Balances|website=www.iea.org|publisher=International Energy Agency (IEA)|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref>

Uzbekistan will be the first country in Central Asia to develop and produce solar energy by [[Uzbekenergo]] a state owned [[Energy industry|energy company]]. The [[Samarqand Region|Samarkand region]] was picked along with six other regions being inspected. The solar power plant is to have a capacity of 100 megawatts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.industryweek.com/expansion-management/uzbekistan-build-first-solar-power-plant|title=Uzbekistan to Build First Solar Power Plant|website=www.industryweek.com|language=en|access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.trend.az/business/energy/2708904.html|title=Chinese company to build solar power plant in Uzbekistan|date=2017-01-14|newspaper=Trend.Az|language=ru-RU|access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref>

