{{Merge to|Exhaust gas|date=October 2018}}
[[File:Bankside power station and St George the Martyr church - geograph.org.uk - 1607688.jpg|thumb|Flue gas from London's [[Bankside Power Station]], 1975]]
'''Flue gas''' is the [[gas]] exiting to the atmosphere via a [[flue]], which is a pipe or channel for conveying exhaust gases from a fireplace, oven, [[furnace]], [[boiler]] or [[Boiler (power generation)|steam generator]]. Quite often, the flue gas refers to the [[combustion]] exhaust gas produced at [[power plants]]. Its composition depends on what is being burned, but it will usually consist of mostly [[nitrogen]] (typically more than two-thirds) derived from the combustion of air, [[carbon dioxide]] ({{CO2}}), and [[water vapor]] as well as excess [[oxygen]] (also derived from the combustion air). It further contains a small percentage of a number of pollutants, such as [[Atmospheric particulate matter|particulate matter]] (like [[soot]]), [[carbon monoxide]], [[nitrogen oxides]], and [[sulfur oxides]].<ref>[http://www.eoearth.org/article/Fossil_fuel_combustion_glue_gases?topic=74180 Fossil fuel combustion flue gases] Milton R. Beychok, Encyclopedia of Earth, 2012.</ref>
==Scrubbing== At power plants, flue gas is often treated with a series of chemical processes and [[scrubber]]s, which remove pollutants. [[Electrostatic Precipitator|Electrostatic precipitators]] or [[Dust collector#Fabric filters|fabric filters]] remove particulate matter and [[flue-gas desulfurization]] captures the [[sulfur dioxide]] produced by burning fossil fuels, particularly coal. Nitrogen oxides are treated either by modifications to the combustion process to prevent their formation, or by high temperature or catalytic reaction with [[ammonia]] or [[urea]]. In either case, the aim is to produce nitrogen gas, rather than nitrogen oxides. In the United States, there is a rapid deployment of technologies to remove [[mercury (element)|mercury]] from flue gas—typically by [[absorption (chemistry)|absorption]] on sorbents or by capture in inert solids as part of the [[flue-gas desulfurization]] product. Such scrubbing can lead to meaningful recovery of sulfur for further industrial use.<ref>[http://www.eoearth.org/article/Sulfur?topic=49557 Sulfur] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028080550/http://www.eoearth.org/article/Sulfur?topic=49557 |date=October 28, 2012 }} C. Michael Hogan, Encyclopedia of Earth, 2011.</ref>
Technologies based on regenerative capture by [[amines]] for the removal of {{CO2}} from flue gas have been deployed to provide high purity {{CO2}} gas to the food industry, and for [[enhanced oil recovery]]. They are now under active research as a method for {{CO2}} capture for long-term storage as a means of [[greenhouse gas remediation]], and have begun to be implemented in a limited way commercially (e.g. the [[Sleipner gas field#Carbon capture and storage project|Sleipner West field]] in the [[North Sea]], operating since 1996).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.statoil.com/en/TechnologyInnovation/ProtectingTheEnvironment/CarboncaptureAndStorage/Pages/CarbonDioxideInjectionSleipnerVest.aspx|title=Technology - Technology and innovation - statoil.com|website=www.statoil.com|language=en|access-date=2017-12-09|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216072031/http://www.statoil.com/en/TechnologyInnovation/ProtectingTheEnvironment/CarboncaptureAndStorage/Pages/CarbonDioxideInjectionSleipnerVest.aspx|archivedate=2009-12-16|df=}}</ref>
There are a number of proven technologies for removing pollutants emitted from power plants that are now available. There is also much ongoing research into technologies that will remove even more air pollutants.{{cn|date=February 2017}}
